An Overview of Puppeteer & The Accessibility Tree

01
On this page

An Overview of Puppeteer

Puppeteer is an API that allows you to run Chrome headlessly. It can crawl single page apps, generate screenshots and PDFs, automate form submissions… pretty much anything you can do in a browser is fair game for automating with Puppeteer.

In this section, we’ll use a library called jest-puppeteer to add the ability to write assertions to expect behavior in Puppeteer that uses the same syntax and structure we’ve already been working with.

This combination gives us some features that aren’t in Cypress but were in an older testing tool called Selenium WebDriver.

While this probably shouldn’t be your only testing tool, Puppeteer combined with jest-puppeteer gives you a lot of capability.

The Accessibility Tree in DevTools

In previous workshops we have seen the Accessibility Tree in DevTools when manually checking our pages. Now we will automate some of that work by using jest-puppeteer to write some assertions against it.

Recall that the Accessibility Tree is a structure that runs parallel to the DOM. It is used by Assistive Technologies to understand what is on the page and how it can be operated.

For example, adding a name, a click event, and a role of button lets a screen reader user know that the element is interactive.

To become familiar with the Accessibility Tree, we can start by visualizing it in the browser.

Inside of DevTools we can look at the structure of the DOM. It contains all of the rendered elements that we have created, including their tag names, attributes, and how CSS styles are applied.

In terms of the accessibility information, this is where it gets interesting.

To the right of “Styles”, “Computed”, and “Layout” in Chrome’s DevTools Elements inspector is an “Accessibility” option.

When you click it, a rendering of the Accessibility Tree is shown.

An Alternative View of the Accessibility Tree

Open a new Chrome tab and navigate to chrome://accessibility.

When you scroll down, you’ll see a list of the browser’s open tabs. Each listing includes a button to show the Accessibility Tree for that tab.

The information in the Accessibility Tree for each tab is exposed to Assistive Technology through platform accessibility APIs on the host operating system.

While it’s not very human readable, this snapshot information enables us to test and write assertions against the Accessibility Tree.

If something changes in the Accessibility Tree snapshot, we’ll know that something has changed that affects the accessibility of our page. We can then review the changes and either accept the new snapshot or use this warning system to help us debug an unexpected change.
